MENINGOCOCCAL DISEASE - UK: RETROSPECTIVE SURVEY (02)
*****************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Meningococcal disease - UK: retrospective survey 971225212820
Date: Fri, 26 Dec 1997 07:44:49 +0000
From: Steve Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
The following background data on meningococcal infection in the U.K. were
abstracted from the GIDEON software program:
Meningococcal infection rates in the U.K. peak during November to January.
Fifty-five percent of patients are below age 5. Fifty-two percent of
meningococci isolated in 1996 were group B and 36.4% group C. Note that
the following data are based on reports of either meningococcal meningitis,
or meningococcal infection.
England & Wales (CDSC):
year meningitis other infections
1980 509
1981 464
1982 410
1983 428
1984 401
1985 550
1986 870
1987 1,080
1988 1,304
1989 1,133 1,362 (203 fatal)
1990 1,138 1,415 (169 fatal)
1991 1,117 1,390 (170 fatal)
1992 n.a. 1,344 (162 fatal)
1993 n.a. 1,451 (173 fatal)
1994 938 1,368 (149 fatal)
1995 1,142 1,847 (196 fatal)
1996 1,177 2,313 (234 fatal)
1997 735 (first half)
- 60% to 70% of recent isolates have been serogroup B. Serogroup C
accounted for 32% in 1995; 39% in 1995; 39% in 1996.
- 45 clusters of meningococcal disease (including 114 cases) were reported
for England and Wales during 1993 to 1995. Three clusters of meningococcal
disease were reported among university students during October to November
1997 (Salford and Southhampton) - including 6 cases (3 fatal) of serogroup
C infection at the University of Southampton.

Northern Ireland reported 19 meningococcal infections in 1991; 27 in 1992;
35 in 1993.
Scotland reported 108 meningococcal infections in 1970; 324 in 1975; 172 in
1980; 136 in 1985; 190 in 1989; 216 in 1990; 207 in 1992; 207 in 1993; 193
in 1995 (66% serogroup B, 29% serogroup C); 210 (59% serogroup B, 37%
serogroup C) in 1996 - 14 fatal. Since 1993, the age distribution of cases
has shifted from 1-to-4 years, to >15 years.
Wales reported 41 cases of meningococcal meningitis in 1981; 67 in 1986; 71
in 1987; 102 in 1988; 91 in 1989; 71 in 1990; 93 in 1991; 103 in 1992; 96
in 1993; 111 in 1994. An outbreak at the University of Cardiff in 1996
included 7 cases of group C infection (2 fatal). Two cases of
meningococcal disease were reported at the University of Wales in Cardiff
during October, 1997.
Nine cases of pneumococcal meningitis were reported in 1986; 6 in 1987; 9
in 1988; 12 in 1989; 13 in 1990; 22 in 1991; 17 in 1992; 19 in 1993.

Twenty-eight cases of _Haemophilus_ meningitis were reported in 1986; 29 in
1987; 34 in 1988; 41 in 1989; 33 in 1990; 21 in 1991; 33 in 1992; 15 in 1993.
